{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dae6446e-41e1-4934-8011-0bdc267ab092","content":"The project file doesn't exist in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the most common for local servers):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — builds and runs your server. You can also use a path to a published DLL: `\"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]`.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (standard for MCP stdio transport).\n\nIf your server uses **SSE/HTTP** transport instead, use:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"sse\",\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:5000/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAfter saving, VS Code should detect the server automatically. You can verify it's connected via the **MCP: List Servers** command in the Command Palette.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9afd2d94-5882-4f98-aa21-fec125d31f43","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"6415:B0AF0:26D82C2:2BADBAA:69EB4E03"},"id":"fbddd10b-f95f-441f-a900-e730e06d2d99","timestamp":"2026-04-24T11:03:40.502Z","parentId":"5700b4d4-83e4-4b73-8eae-a11195b7398b"}
